:"about 1427","1377":"1377","1453":"1453","about 1403":"about 1403","1375":"1375","1428":"1428","1417":"1417","1427":"1427","Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England":"Adderbury, Oxfordshire, England","Berkshire, England":"Berkshire, England","Essex, England":"Essex, England, United Kingdom","Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England":"Baddesley Clinton, Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Baldington","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Bollington  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Bollington","meanings":["English: locative name from Bollington (Cheshire)."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Agnes Baldington was born about 1403, her father, William Baldington, was 29 and her mother, Lady Joan Glendale, was 27. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Denton. She died in 1428, in Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 26."},"et":{"about 1403–1428":"umbes 1403–1428","1394–1435":"1394–1435","1403–1428":"1403–1428","1417–Male":"1417–Surnud","1401–1427":"1401–1427","1427–1453":"1427–1453","1375–1436":"1375–1436","1377–Female"